# Data Structures and Algorithms II

<span class="lead"> </span>

## [Binary Search Trees](../module/recgJOPYUjvQaN2sa)

#### Objectives:

-   Student should be able to describe the properties of a binary tree and the properties of a "perfect" tree
-   Student should be able to recall the time and space complexity, the strengths and weaknesses, and the common uses of a binary search tree
-   Student should be able to construct a binary search tree that can perform basic operations with a logarithmic time complexity

## [Tree Traversal](../module/recS3C67spna4M4HU)

#### Objectives:

-   Student should be able to recall the different traversal types for a binary tree and implement a function to complete the traversal for each type

## [Graphs I](../module/recEPIaHFEriTuU2x)

#### Objectives:

-   Student should be able to describe what a graph is, explain its components, provide examples of its useful applications, and draw each of the different graph types
-   Student should be able to represent a graph as an adjacency list and an adjacency matrix and compare and contrast the respective representations
-   Student should be able to implement user-defined Vertex and Graph classes that allow basic operations

## [Graphs II](../module/recX4dkkIPeJ6JjX6)

#### Objectives:

-   Student should be able to represent a breadth-first-search of a graph in pseudo-code and recall typical applications for its use
-   Student should be able to represent a depth-first-search of a graph in pseudo-code and recall typical applications for its use
-   Student should be able to implement a breadth-first search on a graph
-   Student should be able to implement a depth-first search on a graph
